\begin{remark}[Mathlib precedent]
  Mathlib has the same pattern at one level of abstraction higher: \texttt{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.monoidalCategory} lifts a symmetric monoidal structure from a value category $A$ to $\mathrm{Sheaf}\,J\,A$ provided $J.W$ is monoidal and $A$ has weak sheafification ($J.W$-isomorphisms are detected pointwise after sheafification). The condensed case (\texttt{LightCondensed.instMonoidalCategorySheafLightProfiniteCoherentTopologyModuleCat}) shows this pattern in action. The wrinkle in our situation is that the value category varies with the open set (we have a sheaf of rings, not a fixed ring), so the generic instance \texttt{Sheaf.monoidalCategory} does not apply directly --- instead we adapt the parallel \texttt{LocalizedMonoidal} pattern to the presheaf-of-modules formalism by establishing $W.\texttt{IsMonoidal}$ for $W := L^{-1}(\mathrm{Iso})$. The proof is bookkeeping rather than mathematics: colimit-preservation of left adjoints applied to the (separately colimit-preserving) presheaf-tensor bifunctor.
\end{remark}

