\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Status of $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ and the stalks-level argument]
  Mathematically, $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ is the statement: \emph{if $L(f)$ is an isomorphism in $X.\mathrm{Modules}$, then so is $L(g \triangleleft f)$ for any presheaf of modules $g$} (and symmetrically for right whiskering). Concretely, $L(f)$ is iso iff $f$ becomes iso on each stalk (since sheafification is local), so we must show that $g \triangleleft f$ is stalkwise iso. At the stalk $x$, the presheaf tensor product computes as the $\mathcal O_{X,x}$-balanced tensor product $g_x \otimes_{\mathcal O_{X,x}} f_x$; tensoring with the identity on $g_x$ preserves stalk-level isomorphisms (since base change along a flat module factor preserves isos). This is the stalks-level argument the Lean side is attempting (iter-080 Lane 3). The bookkeeping required is non-trivial because Mathlib does not yet expose the stalk-of-presheaf-tensor identification in the varying-ring case; the alternative routes (closedness via internal hom; \texttt{sheafificationCompToSheaf} to \texttt{AddCommGrpCat}-side $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$) are both blocked because \texttt{MonoidalClosed} for \texttt{PresheafOfModules}\,$R_0$ is absent for varying $R_0$ and \texttt{toPresheaf}\,$R_0$ is not monoidal (it sends a ring-balanced tensor to a $\mathbb Z$-tensor, which differs). The gap-fill remains the only outstanding piece of Phase~C step~C0; it does \emph{not} block downstream consumers, which use $\mathrm{MonoidalCategory}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}$ directly rather than $W.\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ as a hypothesis.
\end{remark}
